22149638.description:
"Itâ€™s about the little eternities that exist in the world around us, itâ€™s about the limitlessness of being, itâ€™s about the joys that encompass the art of living, and itâ€™s about the act of being present, truly present, to experience all of the above. Stonelands travels through various modes of Bliss, from bursts of euphoria and abandon on the more energetic pieces to the stillness and tranquility of others. A great deal of the record weaves through steady, repetitive motions and insistent vocalizations that all feel meditative, regardless of whether they are backdropped by a wall of enveloping sound or a wall of enveloping silence. Rather than trying to impress with sonic curves out of left field, Stonelands bucks the culture that its architect came from and asks you to sit and hold yourself in an introspective embrace. To listen for yourself in the sameness and silence, and to listen for your own voice â€” the one that reminds you of who you are, of what hopes and dreams you have, and of the inner child who is beckoning you to fill with light. All of these moments when you allow yourself to feel it are like affirmations, as if the music is saying, 'You know I love you, right?'"

-E.Y.

The Dallas-born Eric Seall spent the better part of a decade crafting and helping popularize what would come to be known as â€œfuture riddim.â€ While many in his field make music that is equal parts heavy and melodic, those elements are one and the same for Ace Aura; his basses have chords running through their very fibers. 

Inspired by both the brostep of yesteryear and his Christian faith, Seall aims to bring light to the bass music scene by promoting a wholesome lifestyle, musical uniqueness and exceptional production. To say this has caught on would be an understatement, as he has amassed more than 20 million streams on Spotify to date and earned cosigns from just about every A-list bass DJ one could imagine (not the least of which include Skrillex, Zomboy, Seven Lions, NGHTMRE, Flux Pavilion and SLANDER). His presence has graced more than a fair share of coveted stages, including Excisionâ€™s Lost Lands & Bass Canyon, Red Rocks Amphitheatre (as direct support for Subtronics), Electric Zoo and Wobbleland. Everen Maxwell Graves is a San Diego based producer/DJ who is best known for his song "Warbringer" with TheFatRat & Lindsey Stirling, along with his various releases on NCS, Circus Records, The Arcadium, FiXT and Magic Records. Self-described as "music for adventurers," Everen Maxwell takes inspiration from fantasy literature, stories of old and travels abroad to create truly one-of-a-kind EDM songs that evoke a sense of wanderlust and blur the lines between genres. His new EP Stargazing is an ode to the beauty of creation and exploring it with the people you love. "Everywhere I go I can't help but smile and admire the beauty around me, and that's what I wrote the Stargazing EP about," Everen said. "It's a call to see the magic and wonder in creation, an anthem for exploring the world with your favorite people, and a dream of what amazing things might come next." He has also done official remixes for prominent artists such as Derek Minor, Puppet, Ace Aura, Millennial Trash, Phocust, Hyper Fenton, JStu, Moflo Music and Marshall Marshall.

There comes a time in every artistâ€™s career when the art form transcends a mere outlet for self-expression and becomes a universal gift to mankind laced with the necessary genius of its creator. For some it takes years, for 27-year-old Abby Holliday it was there from the start, her vulnerable introspection and brutal lyricism combined with mind-bending sonic sensibilities and a distinct production style that immediately fused a bond between her and her loyal fan base that grows stronger every day. Hailing from Cincinnati, OH now residing in Nashville, TN, Holliday masterfully guides listeners through moments in time extremely specific to her own life that puts words to collective experiences of the human condition, reaching into places we might not have known existed prior. 

Having begun her musical journey on guitar, Abby found her voice during her early years of college where she began quietly writing songs in the confides of her room. After a friend heard the songs and encouraged her to record them, Abby met producer Jonathan Class and set off to record her debut WHEN WEâ€™RE FAR APART I FALL APART. It was in these studio moments where Abbyâ€™s sound began to take shape, a launchpad for her sophomore album Iâ€™M OK NO Iâ€™M NOT. While guitar naturally remains the centerpiece of many of her songs, Holliday and Class explore and experiment with a wide range of sounds from vocoded vocal stacks, to jarring synths, to lush strings and piano, to a tasteful blend of organic and synthetic rhythm sections amassing in a discography that runs the gambit of the most beautiful songs youâ€™ve ever heard to songs that smack you in the face with unforgettable hooks and driving beats. 

With an impressive touring history opening for acts like James Bay, Michigander, Phillip Phillips, The Wldlfe, and more, Abby isnâ€™t after a viral moment or to be a flash in the pan. Rather, she understands the importance of grassroots building on a foundation on authenticity that naturally pours over into her music and live show. The effect is already placing her front and center of the new wave of indie alternative pop/singer-songwriter music.
